950-4052-9ff6-9a44e9cdd86e","timestamp_":"absolute"},"recipient":"all","channel":null},"parent":"5a4ae8b9-8950-4052-9ff6-9a44e9cdd86e","children":["3f3f1d59-7eca-46cc-b36b-4c0f4ea3d0dc"]},"3f3f1d59-7eca-46cc-b36b-4c0f4ea3d0dc":{"id":"3f3f1d59-7eca-46cc-b36b-4c0f4ea3d0dc","message":{"id":"3f3f1d59-7eca-46cc-b36b-4c0f4ea3d0dc","author":{"role":"assistant","name":null,"metadata":{}},"create_time":1753882221.516689,"update_time":null,"content":{"content_type":"text","parts":["Let me tuck the essentials into a single thread of prose, then I\u2019ll hand the baton back to you to check that everything lands clearly.\n\nIn Lagrangian mechanics we begin with a configuration manifold \\(Q\\) whose coordinates I\u2019ll write \\(q^{i}(t)\\).  A **Lagrangian** is a smooth function \\(L: TQ \\times \\mathbb R \\to \\mathbb R,\\; (q,\\dot q,t)\\mapsto L(q,\\dot q,t)\\).  The action functional \\(S[q]=\\int_{t_1}^{t_2} L(q,\\dot q,t)\\,dt\\) is stationary under compactly supported variations \\(\\delta q^{i}(t)\\) precisely when the **Euler\u2013Lagrange equations**\n\n\\[\n\\frac{d}{dt}\\Bigl(\\partial_{\\dot q^{i}}L\\Bigr)-\\partial_{q^{i}}L=0\n\\]\n\nhold.  The quantity \\(p_{i}:=\\partial_{\\dot q^{i}}L\\) is the canonical momentum; the Legendre transform \\(H(q,p,t)=p_{i}\\dot q^{i}-L\\) gives the Hamiltonian when it exists.\n\nNow for continuous symmetries.  Suppose a one\u2011parameter family of coordinate transformations \\(q^{i}\\mapsto q^{i}+\\epsilon\\,\\delta q^{i}\\) leaves \\(L\\) unchanged up to a total time derivative, \\(L\\mapsto L+\\epsilon\\,\\frac{dF}{dt}\\).  Substituting this into the action and integrating by parts shows that the quantity\n\n\\[\nJ=\\delta q^{i}\\,p_{i}-F\n\\]\n\nis conserved along every solution of the Euler\u2013Lagrange equations; that is Noether\u2019s classical theorem in embryo.  The standard exemplars are: invariance under time translation (\\(t\\mapsto t+\\epsilon\\)) gives conservation of energy \\(H\\); spatial translation invariance yields linear momentum \\(\\mathbf p\\); rotational invariance delivers angular momentum \\(\\mathbf L=\\mathbf r\\times\\mathbf p\\).\n\n---\n\n**Your turn, just to anchor the recap.**  Take the free non\u2011relativistic particle with \\(L=\\tfrac12 m\\dot{\\mathbf r}^{2}\\).\n\n1. Starting from \\(L\\), can you write down its canonical momentum \\(\\mathbf p(\\mathbf r,\\dot{\\mathbf r})\\)?  \n(Keep it literal: a single formula.)  \n\nOnce you post that, we\u2019ll check it quickly and use the same example to see Noether\u2019s prescription in action before we quantum\u2011ify anything."]},"status":"finished_successfully","end_turn":true,"weight":1.0,"metadata":{"citations":[],"content_references":[],"gizmo_id":"g-p-6889742efa308191b3e97447d2f94c8d","request_id":"967535cacc8f49c0-SIN","message_type":"next","model_slug":"o3","default_model_slug":"o3","parent_id":"88994511-b53f-4f49-976f-b16d3661d3f0","timestamp_":"absolute"},"recipient":"all","channel":"final"},"parent":"88994511-b53f-4f49-976f-b16d3661d3f0","children":[]}}}